  <tbody>
   <tr>
    <td colspan="7" rowspan="1">
     <bold>Anti-Human immunodeficiency virus type 1 (HIV-1):</bold>
    </td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">1</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">
     <italic>Panax ginseng</italic> Meyer (Korean Red Ginseng, KRG)
    </td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Araliaceae</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Roots</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Capsules</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Prolong survival in HIV-1 patients, possibly by slowing the decrease in CD4
     <sup>+</sup> T-cell count.
    </td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">[
     <xref rid="cit0004" ref-type="bibr">4</xref>]
    </td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">2</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">
     <italic>Betula alba</italic>
    </td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Betulaceae</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Leaves</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Water</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Have interesting immunostimulatory and antimicrobial properties and hence could be useful in the management of HIV/AIDS and associated opportunistic infections</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">[
     <xref rid="cit0012" ref-type="bibr">12</xref>]
    </td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">3</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">
     <italic>Sutherlandia frutescens</italic>
    </td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Fabaceae</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Leaves</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Water</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Have interesting immunostimulatory and antimicrobial properties and hence could be useful in the management of HIV/AIDS and associated opportunistic infections</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">[
     <xref rid="cit0012" ref-type="bibr">12</xref>]
    </td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">4</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">
     <italic>Aerva lanata</italic>
    </td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Amaranthaceae</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Roots</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Chloroform and methanol</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Shows highest inhibition of recombinant HIV RT (91% and 89% respectively) at 1 mg/mL concentration.</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">[
     <xref rid="cit0013" ref-type="bibr">13</xref>]
    </td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">5</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">
     <italic>Moringa oleifera</italic> Lam.
    </td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Moringaceae</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Leaves</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Methanol extract Ethyl ether, methanol and water extract</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Co-administration of leaf powder at the traditional dose did not significantly alter the steady-state PK of nevirapine in HIV-infected active against the HIV-1 lentiviral vector and inhibited the early events of the viral replication cycle on HeLa cells in a concentration dependent manner with IC
     <sub>50</sub> of 7.59 μg/mL, 7.72 μg /mL and 7.17 μg /mL, respectively.
    </td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">[
     <xref rid="cit0014" ref-type="bibr">14</xref>,
     <xref rid="cit0015" ref-type="bibr">15</xref>]
    </td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">7</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">
     <italic>Acacia catechu</italic>
    </td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Mimosa</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Stem bark</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Aqueous and 50% ethanolic extracts</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">A potential anti-HIV-1 activity of A. catechu mediated by the inhibition of the functions of the viral protein and Tat.</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">[
     <xref rid="cit0016" ref-type="bibr">16</xref>]
    </td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">8</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">
     <italic>Phyllanthus emblica</italic>
    </td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Euphorbiaceae</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Fruit</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">n-hexane (HX), carbon tetrachloride (CT), chloroform (CF), and aqueous fractions</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Anti-HIV activity via inhibition of HIV reverse transcriptase activity</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">[
     <xref rid="cit0017" ref-type="bibr">17</xref>]
    </td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">9</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">
     <italic>Sutherlandia frutescens</italic> (L.) R. Br.
    </td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Fabaceae</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Leaves</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Ground to a uniform powder</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Does not causes significant adverse effects in HIV seropositive adults</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">[
     <xref rid="cit0018" ref-type="bibr">18</xref>]
    </td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">10</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">
     <italic>Pinus yunnanensis</italic> Franch
    </td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Pinaceae</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Pine cones</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">95% ethanol extract</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">These data suggest that the pine cone extract from 
     <italic>Pinus yunnanensis</italic>
     <break/>has potent inhibitory activities against HIV-1
     <sub>IIIB</sub>, HIV-1
     <sub>RF</sub>, RT inhibitor-resistant strains HIV-1
     <sub>A17</sub> and HIV-1
     <sub>AO18</sub>, and HIV-2
     <sub>ROD</sub>, and its anti-HIV mechanisms include inhibition of HIV entry and inhibition of reverse transcriptase activity.
    </td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">[
     <xref rid="cit0019" ref-type="bibr">19</xref>]
    </td>
   </tr>
   <tr>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">12</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">
     <italic>Alepidea amatymbica</italic>
    </td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Umbelliferae</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Whole plants</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Aqueous extract</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">Showed significant selective anti-HIV activity</td>
    <td rowspan="1" colspan="1">[
     <xref rid="cit0020" ref-type="bibr">20</xref>]
    </td>
   </tr>
